post_text:
And on that day....time stood still.

Today marks 19 years since the tragic 9/11 terrorist attacks, a day now known as Patriot Day.

Former President George W. Bush declared the first Patriot Day just before Sept. 11 in 2002.

On Sept. 11, 2001, terrorists hijacked four planes. Two of them crashed into both World Trade Center towers in New York, causing them to collapse.

Another crashed into the Pentagon while a fourth went down in a field in Shanksville, Pennsylvania after passengers struggled with hijackers.

This Patriot Day, we commemorate the lives of those who perished on September 11, 2001, we honor the families who carry on their legacies, and we thank the unmatched bravery of our Nation‚Äôs first responders.

#NeverForget #Honor911 #WorldTradeCenter #Pentagon #Flight93 #GroundZero #Heroes #September11 #ThankYouFirstResponders

post_text: Labor Day is a federal holiday in the United States celebrated on the first Monday in September to honor and recognize the American labor movement and the works and contributions of laborers to the development and achievements of the United States. It is the Monday of the long weekend known as Labor Day Weekend.

On August 31, 2020, the U.S. Department of Agriculture extended the opportunity for Nutrition Services to extend free meals to all students through December 31, 2020. Parents, we need your help! Campbell County Prevention Council is partnering with Campbell County School District, Public Health, Y.E.S. House, Juvenile Probation, Juvenile Diversion, Gillette Police Department and Campbell County Sheriff‚Äôs Office for a Virtual Town Hall Meeting in September. (date has not been set yet, and will be announced later)

We are collecting questions for the Town Hall about Electronic Nicotine Delivery Systems (ENDS), aka E-cigarettes or Vaping in reference to your child. Please email your questions to Jessica Diaz, CCSD Student Assistance Coordinator at Student Support Services at jdiaz@ccsd.k12.wy.us. We will take your questions seriously and answer them in detail during the virtual meeting. Please indicate in the email if you do not want your name announced with the question at the virtual meeting.Thank you!

Please do not post your questions on this post, they must be emailed to Mrs. Diaz! Thank you!

Another BIG shoutout to our amazing Print Shop Manager Mandy Love and amazing staff Anita Deaton, Kristal Hedlund, Carla Hutton, and Jessica Pilcher, for all their amazing work during the adapted learning process. By the numbers to date:
768 orders printed and sent home to students, resulting in 14,750 home deliveries
59,000 food prep instructions printed for Nutrition Services
2,667 Yearbooks printed

Attention Future Kindergarten Parents!

Any student who has been registered for the 2020-2021 school term will have their Kindergarten screening held the week of June 15-19. Elementary schools will be contacting parents with the date and time for the screening. Screenings will be rescheduled for the week of July 13-17 if the situation with COVID-19 does not allow for screenings to occur during the June window. If you have questions, please contact your child's school. Thank you.
text:
Attention Future Kindergarten Parents!

Any student who has been registered for the 2020-2021 school term will have their Kindergarten screening held the week of June 15-19. Elementary schools will be contacting parents with the date and time for the screening. Screenings will be rescheduled for the week of July 13-17 if the situation with COVID-19 does not allow for screenings to occur during the June window. If you have questions, please contact your child's school. Thank you.

post_text:
Governor Mark Gordon issued an order on March 27, 2020, extending school closures through April 17. CCSD#1 has submitted the required Adaptive Learning Plan to the Wyoming Department of Education (WDE) that would allow, with WDE approval, for remote education to begin on April 6 and last the length of this closure order. The plan is designed to accommodate any further extensions.

Wyoming school districts have been working closely with State Superintendent Jillian Balow in the development of Adapted Learning Plans in preparation for possible school closures. Following Governor Gordon's order today, Superintendent Balow issued a statement regarding guidance for continued education during school closures. School staff is contacting families at this time in preparation for continued education. Once the district receives State approval, CCSD will publish individual school remote learning plans. We anticipate approval the week of March 30.

Thank you for your patience. Please visit the CCSD website for future updates.

March 4 at 12:55 PM ¬∑

Did you know that three out of every five home fires deaths resulted from fires in homes with no smoke alarms (38%) or no working smoke alarms (21%)?? It‚Äôs a scary yet true statistic!!!

On Sunday, March 8th, when you set your clocks forward don‚Äôt forget to change the batteries in your smoke detector and carbon monoxide detector. Too often we go on calls and find these detectors without batteries or even worse, removed and sitting on the counter. Smoke detectors and carbon monoxide detectors save lives so let‚Äôs make sure yours is working!

It's Dr. Suess' birthday and Read Across America Day!

Read Across America is a day held annually on March 2nd that encourages children in every community to read and also encourages parents and teachers to celebrate the joy of reading. It‚Äôs a holiday that has been celebrated since 1998 and falls on the same day as children‚Äôs book author Dr. Seuss.

March 2 is the birthday of Theodore Seuss Geisel, an American author who, under the pen name Dr. Seuss, wrote and illustrated some of the world‚Äôs most iconic children‚Äôs books. His rhymes and characters are beloved by generations of fans.

‚ÄúToday you are you! That is truer than true! There is no one alive who is Youer than You!‚Äù

#drsuessbirthday

Mrs.Torres Guernsey, music teacher at Paintbrush Elementary, shared the video of her 6th grade Honor Choir performing at the February 12 School Board meeting and the story behind it. WOW! üëèüëèüëè

"The song the honor choir sang is SO powerful! It is called "Nothing More" by The Alternate Routes, and it speaks to a message that at the end of the day, all that really matters is how we've treated others. The driving lyric in this song "we are how we treat each other, and nothing more" really impacted me when I first heard it, and I knew I wanted to share it with my students this year when Mrs. Gilson said one of our driving statements at Paintbrush would be "Be Brave & Be Kind." We, as a choir, discussed what the words meant, and these musicians had a lot of great insights." Mrs. Torres Guernsey

#BeKind #KindnessMatter #BeBrave

post_text:
INTRODUCING THE NEW LAKEVIEW ELEMENTARY HOPE SQUAD! üëèüëè The students along with their advisors, Ms. Boedeker-Larson and Ms. Burbank are very excited to start their new venture! As one student stated "Sometimes all that people need is a smile to start their day, and one of the first things we will be doing is greeting everyone in the mornings with a smile on our face!" ‚ò∫Ô∏è

HOPE (Hold On, Persuade, Empower) Squads aim at identifying, protecting, and assisting students. HOPE Squads are the eyes and ears of the school. Squad members provide friendship, kindness, inclusion, identify warning signs, and seek help from adults if needed for their peers. Members are not taught to act as counselors, but rather are educated to recognize signs that a student is struggling and respectfully report concerns to an adult.

#HopeSquad #GivingHope

The National Youth Science Camp is an annual education experience for recent high school graduates. Held each summer at Camp Pocahontas near Thornwood, West Virginia, the camp allows two students from each state to participate. The camp will be held June 22-July 15, 2020.
Applicants must have graduated from high school between July 1, 2019, and June 30, 2020. Deadline to register is February 28, 2020: https://nysf.smapply.io/

The National Youth Science Camp is an annual education experience for recent high school graduates. Held each summer at Camp Pocahontas near Thornwood, West Virginia, the camp allows two students from each state to participate. The camp will be held June 22-July 15, 2020.
Applicants must have graduated from high school between July 1, 2019, and June 30, 2020. Deadline to register is February 28, 2020: https://nysf.smapply.io/
